{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.95,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79172"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10871"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64524"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25289"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79172"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAdhesive capsulitis, commonly referred to as frozen shoulder, involves pain and restricted movement to the shoulder joint. It is often seen in individuals aged 40 to 60 and can be associated with conditions e.g. diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of adhesive capsulitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Degeneration of the rotator cuff tendons","Dislocation of the shoulder joint","Inflammation and thickening of the joint capsule","Tear of the glenoid labrum","Calcification of the shoulder ligaments"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of adhesive capsulitis involves \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammation and thickening of the joint capsule\u003C/strong\u003E. This process leads to the formation of adhesions and fibrosis which restricts movement in the shoulder joint. The condition is characterised by pain and a progressive loss of both active and passive range of motion in the shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegeneration of the rotator cuff tendons\u003C/strong\u003E - This is associated with rotator cuff tendinopathy, not adhesive capsulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification of the shoulder ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E - describes calcific tendinitis, not adhesive capsulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDislocation of the shoulder joint\u003C/strong\u003E - is a separate condition involving displacement of the humeral head\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETear of the glenoid labrum\u003C/strong\u003E - is associated with labral tears, not adhesive capsulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adhesive capsulitis, also known as frozen shoulder, involves inflammation and thickening of the shoulder joint capsule.","The condition leads to the formation of adhesions and fibrosis within the joint capsule, restricting shoulder movement.","Adhesive capsulitis is characterised by pain and progressive loss of both active and passive shoulder range of motion."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Wang K, Ho V, Hunter-Smith DJ, Beh PS, Smith KM, Weber AB. Risk factors in idiopathic adhesive capsulitis: a case control study. J Shoulder Elbow Surg. 2013 Jul;22(7):e24-9. doi: 10.1016/j.jse.2012.10.049. Epub 2013 Jan 24. PMID: 23352186.","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences250","Le HV, Lee SJ, Nazarian A, Rodriguez EK. Adhesive capsulitis of the shoulder: review of pathophysiology and current clinical treatments. Shoulder Elbow. 2017 Apr;9(2):75-84. doi: 10.1177/1758573216676786. Epub 2016 Nov 7. PMID: 28405218; PMCID: PMC5384535."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64524"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64524"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:01:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:02:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10871"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79172"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"